column85: Cont1 Valve Or Device Fail Ind
column168: Description Of Events

MISSING MANWAY COVER GASKET, CGTX 21052, FEBRUARY 1, 2001 NORTH JERSEY DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 2230 HOURS, THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 1, 2001, AT PORT READING YARD IN PORT READING NEW JERSEY, A CONRAIL CONDUCTOR NOTED PRODUCT ALONG SIDES OF TANK CAR CGTX 21052 CONTAINING ISOPROPANOL.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  RECAT ARRIVED AT THE SITE EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THERE WAS A MISSING MANWAY COVER GASKET.  THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED AND OKAYED FOR DESTINATION.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TANK TRUCK RAN OFF COUNTY ROAD WITH NO SHOULDER, OVERTURNED AND RUPTURED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER HAD FINISHED LOADING, AND HAD HOOKED UP A NITROGEN HOSE TO OUR BLEEDER VALVE FOR THE PURPOSE OF BLOWING THE EXCESS ACID FROM OUR HOSE BACK INTO THE CUSTOMERS TANK.  THE NITROGEN HOSE CAME LOOSE AND THE ACID WAS BLOWN BACK THRU THE BLEEDER VALVE ONTO THE DRIVER, AND INTO THE CONTAINED AREA.  THE OPERATOR WASHED DOWN THE ACID INTO THEIR DRAIN.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER HAD HIS PAPERWORK SIGNED BY PLANT OPERATOR.  PLANT OPERATOR INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVER TO UNLOAD INTO THEIR TANK.  THE DRIVER DID NOT HAVE A CLEAR VIEW OF THE CUSTOMERS TANKS AND HE SHUT EVERYTHING DOWN WHEN THE PLANT OPERATOR TOLD HIM THAT THEIR TANK HAD OVERFLOWED.  MICHELIN ACCEPTED FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE CLEAN-UP.  MICHELIN CALLED IN R&D CLEANING TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILL.  THIS SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN A CONTAINMENT AREA.

ON HOOKING UP THE PRODUCT TRANSFER FROM THE TRAILER TO THE CONSIGNEE RECEIVING LINE, WHEN THE DRIVER PLACED THE HOSE CONNECTION INTO THE RECEIVING LINE FITTING, HE FAILED TO CHECK FOR A GASKET. ON STARTING TO UNLOAD PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO UNLOADING AREA. GASKET WAS INSTALLED & UNLOADING COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP OF THE SPILL AREA.

DISCOVERED CARTON SLIGHTLY WET WHEN REENFORCING, BOTTOM FLAP WITH TAPE WEARING FULL PPE I FOLLOWED DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAM.  LIQUID SPILL.  FOLLOWED STEPS FOR PROCESSING WASTE THROUGH DMP.  NO ITEM DAMAGE PER SHPR PACKAGE WAS FORWARD TO CONSIGNEE.
CUSTOMER TANK OVERFLOWED BECAUSE SITE GAUGE WAS FAULTY.  PRODUCT WENT RIGHT INTO SYSTEM.
CUSTOMER UNLOADING INTO A WOODEN KEG AND THE METAL BAND CAME OFF.
PACKAGE WAS PUNCTURED.  I PROCEEDED TO PROCESS AND DISPOSE OF PACKAGE FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.  BETTER HANDLING OF PACKAGE WILL PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: DSI VEHICLE TOWING  NORTH ON HWY 421 AT PENDERLEA COMMUNITY ON THE WAY TO CUSTOMER RAN OFF ROAD WAY RESULTING IN ROLLOVER.  THIS CAUSED PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM DOME LIDS ON TANK.

column168: AT APROX 22:20 HOURS I WAS INFORMED BY TONY WILLIAMS THAT THERE MAY BE A HAZMAT SPILL TONY WAS WORKING TRAILER 8543 FROM DSP. HE HAD THREE BOXES ON A FLOAT OUT IN THE BAY BEHIND THE TRAILER. ONE OF THE BOXES HAD STARTED LEAKING WHILE ON THE FLOAT.HE GAVE ME THE BILL SEEING THAT IT WAS HAZMAT. I INSTRUCTED HIM TO PULL THE FLOAT TO OUR HAZMAT BAY AND SECURE THE AREA. I THEN CHECKED THE ERG. AFTER CHECKING THE ERG, I PUT OUT HAZMAT PROTECTIVE GEAR ON AND OPENED THE BOX FOR INVESTIGATION. I SEEN A CRACK IN ONE OF THE CONTAINERS LID ABOUT HALF OF THE CONTENTS OF THE 16OZ BOTTLE HAD LEAKED OUT AND WAS INSIDE THE BOX, THE BOX WAS LINED IN PLASTIC. I ASKED TONY HOW THE BOX CAME OFF THE TRAILER. HE SAID IT WAS UPSIDE DOWN ON THE FLOOR AND APPEARED TO HAVE FELL ANOTHER BOX IN ROUTE. I THEN CALLED OUR HAZMAT EMERGENCY CENTER AT THE GENERAL OFFICE AND WAS PUT IN CONTACT WITH EDDIE YANCE. I EXPLAINED EVERYTHING TO HIM. I THEN FOLLOWED HIS CLEAN-UP INSTRUCTIONS. I THEN CALLED INFOTRAC AND THEY FAXED ME THE MSDS. I WAS ALSO GIVEN INSTRUCTIONS TO LEAVE OUR OS&D CLERK INSTRUCTIONS TO CALL THE SHIPPER AND GET DISPOSITION.

SHPX203500 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM SUMP AREA WHILE THE CAR WAS IN THE CSX TRANSPORTATION HAWTHORNE YARD, INDIANAPOLIS, IN.  THE CAR WAS LOADED WITH CUPRIC CHLORIDE, A CORROSIVE MATERIAL.  STEADY STREAMS WERE COMING FROM THE SUMP AREA OF THE CAR.  THE CONSIGNEE BROUGHT VACUUM TRUCKS AND TRANSFERRED PRODUCT INTO THE VACUUM TRUCKS FOR TRANSPORTATION TO CONSIGNEE FACILITY.  AS THE TRANSFER PROGRESSED, THE CAR BEGAN LEAKING AT SEVERAL OTHER LOCATIONS, SUCH AS THE STUB SILL CONNECTS TO CAR ON BOTH ENDS AND AT THE WELDS ON THE TANK IN VARIOUS LOCATIONS.  INVESTIGATION IS UNDERWAY BY CAR OWNERS AND BUILDERS TO DETERMINE WHY THE CAR FAILED.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND THE PRODUCT WAS CAPTURED IN SPILL PANS PLACED UNDER LEAKS (UMLER RECORDS SHOW THE CAR TO BE A DOT111A100W1) NARRI= 2 (5+5+0) X(4+0) =80;  CAUSE CODE-438

AS CARGO RUNNER WAS LOADING BOXES TO TAKE TO OUTBOUND FLIGHT, HE NOTICED A STRONG ODOR EMITTING FROM ONE BOX.  THIS BOX WAS FOUND TO HAVE A STAIN ON ONE CORNER.  BOX CONTAINED FOUR 1 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINERS OF CLEAR LIQUID LABELED "MATTHEW #10 THINNER".  TWO OF THE CONTAINER'S LABELS SHOWED SIGNS OF STAIN, AS WELL AS FIBREBOARD DIVIDERS INSIDE BOX.  THERE DID NOT APPEAR TO BE ANY DAMAGE TO ANY OF THE FOUR CONTAINERS WHICH WOULD HAVE CAUSED A LEAK, THEREFORE IT IS THOUGHT THAT ONE OR MORE CAP MY HAVE BEEN TIPPED, CAUSING A SMALL AMOUNT TO SPILL.  LIQUID WAS ENTIRELY ABSORBED IN THE FIBERBOARD WAS ENTIRELY ABSORBED IN THE FIBREBOARD BOX  DIVIDERS.  LIDS ON THE CONTAINERS WERE TIGHTENED.  IT WAS DIFFICULT TO DETERMINE WHICH CONTAINER MAY HAVE LEAKED.  AS NONE OF THE CONTAINERS APPEARED TO HAVE A SHORTAGE OF CONTENTS.

column168: UPON OPENING THE DOOR TO TRL. #263402, I NOTICED A HAZ MAT DRUM WITH A SKID WEDGED BETWEEN IT AND THE TRL. DOOR.  WHEN I PULLED THE SKID AWAY FROM THE DRUM, I NOTICED THE CARDBOARD UNDER THE DRUM WAS WET.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF DRUM, I FOUND A SMALL HOLE NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. IT WAS LEAKING.  I THEN FOUND THE DOCK LEAD-MAN AND TOLD HIM OF THE SITUATION.  WE MOVED THE DRUM TO OS & D AND HE HANDLED IT FROM THERE.

SHIPMENT AN HAR SUNDAY 02/04 @ 16:06 ON TRLR 286318.  UNLOADING BEGAN 09:00 02/05.  AFTER THIS PALLET HAD BEEN SET ON DOCK, LEAKAGE WAS NOTED.  DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAID ON SIDE WITH SOURCE OF LEAK FACING UP.  MATERIAL DRIED IMMEDIATELY.  DOCK WORKERS DID NOT NOTICE DAMAGE, AS THE DENT HAD BEEN TURNED TO INSIDE OF SKID IE 3 DRUMS ON SKID WITH DENT NOT FACING OUTWARD.

DAMAGED DRUM WAS ON THE REAR OF THE INBOUND TRAILER FOUND IN AN UPSIDE DOWN POSITION WITH CLEAR TAPE WRAPPED AROUND THE DRUM COVERING WHAT APPEARED TO BE A FORKLIFT BLADE PUNCTURE.  THIS DAMAGE OBVIOUSLY HAPPENED AT THE PREVIOUS LOADING FACILITY.  THE DRUM SHOULD HAVE BEEN PULLED OFF THE TRAILER AND KEPT AT THE LOADING SERVICE CENTER INSTEAD OF BEING SHIPPED ON. THE INDIVIDUAL RESPONSIBLE FOR THE DAMAGE SHOULD BE ISSUED A CORRECTIVE ACTION REPORT AND TAKE REMEDIAL FORKLIFT TRAINING.  DAMAGED DRUM WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER IN A RECOVERY DRUM.

SKID OF FREIGHT WAS ON THE LOADING DOCK WAITING TO BE LOADED ON A DELIVERY TRAILER.  FORKLIFT OPERATOR PICKED UP THE SKID OF FREIGHT TO MOVE IT AWAY FROM OTHER DOCKED FREIGHT SO HE COULD SHRINKWRAP THE CARTONS ON THE SKID. WHEN HE PICKED UP THE SKID ONE OF THE CARTONS FELL OFF FROM THE BACK OF THE SKID AND HIT THE CONCRETE FLOOR.  THE IMPACT SPLIT THE PLASTIC ON ONE OF THE JUGS CAUSING PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT IN THE CARTON AND ON THE FLOOR. DAMAGED CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.  FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS ISSUED A WRITTEN CORRECTIVE ACTION REPORT AND REQUIRED TO ATTEND A REMEDIAL FORKLIFT TRAINING CLASS.

CTR MINI HUB DRIVER WAS HELPING DOCKWORKER UNLOAD TRAILER AND WHEN HE TRIED TO MOVE DRUM WITH FORKLIFT DRUM WAS PUNCTURED CAUSING APP 2 GAL TO LEAK OUT DRUM WAS OVERPACKED IN CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS.  PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED BY ABSORBMENT MATERIAL.  DEBRIS WILL BE DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE LAWS.

SHIPMENT WAS RECEIVED IN HARRISBURG PA ON REAR OF TRAILER.  DRUM HAD CARDBOARD UNDER IT TO ABSORB SHOCK AND DOCKWORKER NOTICED THAT CARDBOARD WAS WET.  INSPECTION FOUND SMALL CRACK IN BOTTOM OF DRUM.  DRUM DID NOT LOOK AS IF IT HAD BEEN DROPPED OR HIT SO CAUSE OF CRACK IS UNKNOWN.  DRUM WAS PLACED IN OVERPACK AND  WILL BE RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER HIS INSTRUCTIONS.

column168: SAFEWAY DRIVER WAS EASTBOUND ON INTERSTATE HWY 12.  HE ATTEMPTED TO EXIT ONTO INTERSTATE HWY 59 AT SLIDELL, LOUISIANA.  HE EXITED TOO FAST AND THE LIQUID IN THE TRAILER SURGED, CAUSING THE TRUCK & TRAILER TO OVERTURN.  THE AUTHORITIES  WERE CALLED "RIGHT TO KNOW" FOR THE STATE OF LOUISIANA WAS CALLED.  THE ST. TAMMANY FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED. OIL MOP HAZ MAT CLEAN UP WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP ABOUT 100 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK WAS TAKEN TO ST TAMMANY HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED AND HAVE A DRUG SCREEN.  ROAD RUNNER WRECKER SERVICE UPRIGHTED THE TRUCK & TRAILER.  THE PRODUCT WAS OFF LOADED ONTO ANOTHER SAFEWAY TRAILER AND DELIVERED BY ANOTHER DRIVER.  SPILLED PRODUCT TAKEN & DISPOSED OF BY OIL MOP.  THE WRECKER SERVICE TOWED WRECKED TRUCK & TRAILER TO THEIR YARD IN BATON ROUGE, LOUISIANA.  THE DRIVER THAT OVERTURNED THE TRUCK & TRAILER WAS TERMINATED.

AFTER  MOLTEN SULFUR COOLED AND HARDENED, THE DRIVER CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE.

column168: DECLARED LEAKING PACKAGES FOUND IN UPS FACILITY

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: THIS PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE DELIVERY OPERATION. THE PACKAGE WAS INSPECTED AND THE PACKING LIST STATED THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX WAS BATTERY.  THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED BOX HAD NO DANGEROUS GOODS DECLARATION PAPERWORK ASSOCIATED WITH IT AND WAS HELD FOR INVESTIGATION.  I WAS NOTIFIED BY THE COURIER AND ADVISED THEM TO HOLD THE PACKAGE UNTIL WE RECEIVED THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  I CONTACTED THE SHIPER, ROSANNA SKIBICKI ABOUT THE INCIDENT AND SHE FAXED ME THE MSDS.  I CONTACTED LOIS UMLAND OF THE DFW/CASFO TO ADVISE HER OF THE INCIDENT AND THAT THE PACKAGE WOULD BE HELD PENDING THEIR INVESTIGATION.  I FAXED ALL THE DOCUMENTATION TO HER AND ADVISED HER THAT THE PACKAGE HAD NEVER FLOWN AND BEEN TRANSPORTED ONLY BY GROUND OPERATION.  DEE ROSE OF THE DFW/CASFO CALLED ME ON 2-9 TO ADVISE ME THAT THE FAA WOULD NOT BE INVESTIGATION THIS SHIPMENT. I ADVISED THE SHIPPER ON 2 - 12 AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR THE SHIPMENT TO BE RETURNED BY GROUND TRANSPORTION.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION.  THE PACKAGE WAS OBSERVED TO HAVE FALLEN OFF A SORT BELT AND THE INNER CONTAINER FAILED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS OBSERVED TO HAVE FALLEN OFF A SORT BELT AND THE INNER CONTAINER FAILED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED REGARDING A DISPOSITION.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION. THE PLASTIC DRUM WAS NOTICED TO HAVE FALLEN FROM A CONVEYOR BELT TO THE GROUND AND THE LID FAILED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND IT WAS TO RETURNED BACK TO THE ORIGIN.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVER TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED REGARDING A DISPOSITION.

I RESPONDED TO A LEAKING PACKAGE IN FULL PPE.  I FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS.  I THEN PROCESSED TI THROUGH THE DMP.

RESPONDED TO DR 88 W/HAZ CART REFERED TO DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEETS FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID. CLAY MATERIAL USED TO ABSORB SPILL. SODIUM BICARB USED TO NEUTRALIZE. TRASH PLACED IN PLASTIC BAG FOR DISPOSAL VIA DMP.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: AT 10:00 PM I RECEIVED A CALL FOR A LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET I WENT TO PICK UP THE SPILL WEARING MY PPE. THE PACKAGE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM. NO CLEAN UP WAS NEEDED AT SITE
FOUND IN TRAILER. IT WAS TRANSPORTED TO GOLD BELT AND DISPOSED OF USING THE D.M.P. PROCESS. CLEANED AND STORED EQUIPMENT.
I RESPONDED TO RED BELT IN FULL PPE. I USED THE DECISION TREE AND THE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS GUIDE PAGE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. I THEN CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP..

RECEIVED PHONE CALL ABOUT FLAMMABLE HAZMAT LEAKER IN SECONDARY. RESPONDER TO LEAKER WEARING PPE AFTER REVIEWING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET LEAK WAS CONTAINED TO CARTON. RETURNED TO DMP AREA FOR PROCESSING OF CONTAMINATED MATERIALS.

THE CONSIGNEE HAD THEIR OWN CLEAN-UP CREW ON SITE AND THEY CLEANED UP THE SPILL AREA AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM SO THAT THE CONSIGNEE WOULD ACCEPT THE WHOLE LOAD.  THE LOAD WAS ACCEPTED AND THE DRIVER CONTINUED ON TO THE NEXT PICK UP POINT.

column168: DRIVER BECAME AWARE OF A DRUM LEAKING IN HIS TRAILER ENROUTE TO DELIVERY. DRIVER USED TRUCK SPILL KIT TO CONTAIN SPILL, SECURED DRUM AND RETURNED TO TERMINAL.  AT TERMINAL IT WAS OBSERVED THAT A PIECE OF PIPE HAD SHIFTED IN TRANSIT AND SLIGHTLY PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE CONTAINER AND RETURN TO SHIPPER AS INSTRUCTED.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND DISPOSED OF BY:  ELDREDGE INC., 898 FERNHILL ROAD, WEST CHESTER, PA. 19380.  SOME DUNNAGE AND BETTER SECUREMENT OF OTHER FREIGHT COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS INCIDENT.  DOCK WORKERS WERE MADE AWARE OF THIS INCIDENT AND DISCUSSED PREVENTION IN THE FUTURE.

THESE TWO BOXES WHERE STAGED ON OUR DOCK.  FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS STAGING OTHER FREIGHT NEAR THEM AND DID NOT NOTICE THE TWO BOXES AND STRUCK THEM WITH FORKLIFT.  DAMAGED BOTTLES WHERE PLACED IN A SALVAGE CONTAINER ALONG WITH CLEANUP MATERIAL AND IS AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION.  FORKLIFT OPERATOR COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS IF HE PAID MORE ATTENTION TO HIS SURROUNDINGS AND CHECKED ALL CLEARANCES AT ALL TIMES.

WHILE LOADING FREIGHT, THIS PARTICULAR DRUM WAS HIT BY ANOTHER PALLET BY DOCK WORKER AND A VERY MINOR PUNCTURE WAS DISCOVERED AS A RESULT.  DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAID ON ITS SIDE AND REPAIRED WITH DRUM PUTTY.  DRUM WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE CONTAINER ALONG WITH THE ABSORBENTS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND WAS DISPOSED OF BY:  ELDREDGE INC., 898 FERNHILL ROAD, WEST CHESTER, PA., 19380.

A VAPOR RECOVERY VALVE ON THE CARGO TANK WAS INADVERTENTLY LEFT OPEN.  WHEN PRODUCT WAS  MOVED OFF THE LOADING RACK, SURGE CAUSED PRODUCT TO ENTER THE VAPOR LINE RESULTING IN APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLING ONTO THE ROAD SURFACE WITH ROHM AND HAAS'S FACILITY.  VALVE WAS CLOSED ONCE IT WAS REALIZED IT WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP BY PLANT PERSONNEL.

column168: DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, ONE OPEN CARTON, CONTAINING FOUR, ONE-HALF GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE JUG WAS DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING THREE WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE JUG WAS A RESULT OF PACKAGING FAILURE. THE TAPE ON THE CARTON APPARENTLY FAILED, CAUSING ONE JUG TO FALL OUT. THE CAP ON  JUG FELL OFF CAUSING THE FREE PRODUCT TO RELEASE. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, DAMAGED JUG, AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE THREE UNAFFECTED JUGS WERE REPACKAGED IN THE ORIGINAL CARTON AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Water Damage; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING ONE, FIVE GALLON PLASTIC JUG WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TEN OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT, CAUSING THE CARTON  TO LAND UPSIDE DOWN AND CRUSHING THE TOP OF THE JUG. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENT. THE CLEANUP  MATERIALS, WET CARTON, DAMAGED JUG AND REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE ON THE DOCK,ONE FORTY-FOUR POUND BAG WAS APPARENTLY DAMAGE BY A FORKLIFT BLADE. APPROXIMATELY TWO CUPS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED ONE EMPLOYEE'S CLOTHING. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INCORPORATED OF GUTHRIE, OK WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INCORPORATED PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING AN ABSORBENT MAT. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS,AFFECTED CLOTHING, FREE PRODUCT, DAMAGED BAG AND REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INCORPORATED WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE DRUM. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE EXPOSED EMPLOYEE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FROM CONCENTRA MEDICAL CENTER ON 7779 SOUTH HARLEM AVENUE IN BRIDGEVIEW, ILLINOIS. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: A TANK TRUCK HAD JUST BEEN LOADED WITH WASTE SOLVENT CONTAINING PETROLEUM DISTILLATES.  THE DRIVER PASSED THROUGH THE CONCRETE AND ASPHALT PARKING AREA OF THE FACILITY AND STOPPED TO CLOSE THE FRONT GATES.  WHILE CLOSING THE GATE, HE NOTICED A TRAIL OF SOLVENT BEHIND HIS TRUCK AND PROCEEDED TO INSPECT HIS TANK DISCOVERING A LEAKING VALVE.  THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED AS WASTE.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 75 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD IN DENETON, TX FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

REPAIR PUTTY WAS PLACED ALONG CRACK ALONG WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED OVER A RECOVERY CONTAINER.  SHIPPER SENT AN EMPTY IBC CONTAINER ALONG WITH A RECOVERY CREW WHO TRANSFERRED THE PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED IBC TO THE REPLACEMENT ONE.

WHILE UNLOADING, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DETECTED A RELEASE OF FREE PRODUCT COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE DOCK AREA WAS EVACUATED AND THE DURHAM FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE ENTIRE FACILITY WAS EVACUATED FOR APPROXIMATELY ONE AND A HALF HOURS.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE TRAILER BY THE DURHAM FIRE DEPARTMENT, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE, THIRTY POUND STEEL CYLINDER WAS LEAKING IN THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE VALVE.  DURHAM FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL TIGHTENED THE LOOSE VALVE ON THE LEAKING CYLINDER.  AIRCO GASES PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE TERMINAL TO REMOVE THE CYLINDER FROM THE TRAILER.  THE CYLINDER WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE AIRCO GASES FACILITY IN RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, NORTH CAROLINA.  THERE WERE REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: WHILE IN THE TERMINAL YARD,  TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED FREE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE LEAKING FOUR THOUSAND NINE HUNDRED AND THIRTY POUND STEEL TOTE WAS DISCOVERED AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY FIFTEEN GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE CAP.  MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL OF CORPUS CHRISTI, TEXAS WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE CAP ON THE LEAKING TOTE WAS TIGHTENED AND THE TOTE WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  TWO, ROADWAY EXPRESS EMPLOYEES WERE EXPOSED TO THE PRODUCT.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NECESSARY.

WHILE UNLOADING, TWO WET CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING TWO, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS, WERE DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT TWO OF THE JUGS WERE DAMAGED AND TWO WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY TWO QUARTS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINERS WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, ABSORBENTS, AND BAKING SODA.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT, WET CARTONS, DAMAGED JUGS, AND UNAFFECTED JUGS WERE PLACED INTO A FORTY GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE FROZEN, FIVE GALLON PLASTIC PAIL WAS DISCOVERED AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING.  HAZ-MAT ONE OF OLATHE, KANSAS WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  HAZ-MAT ONE DISPATCHED WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL OF MISSOULA, MONTANA TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FROZEN PAIL WERE PLACED INTO TWO, FORTY FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUMS THAT WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING 350 GALLON STEEL TOTE TANK WAS DISCOVERED AT THE THREE QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP WHICH WAS PRESSING ON A VALVE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED GLOVES, AMPHOMAG, AN ABSORBENT PAD AND A SHOVEL TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  ONCE THE FREIGHT ON TOP WAS REMOVED, THERE WAS NO FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE VALVE DID NOT APPEAR TO BE LOOSE OR DAMAGED AND THE TOTE TANK WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WAS NO REMAINDER OF SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, TWO 125-GALLON POLY TOTES WERE DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TWO CUPS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED ONTO NEARBY DUNNAGE.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO LOOSE BUNGS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS AND THE AFFECTED DUNNAGE WERE PLACED INTO ONE, 85-GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM, ONE, 55-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, AND TWO, 10-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS.  ALL FOUR RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LOOSE BUNGS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE TOTES WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, A STRONG ODOR WAS DETECTED COMING FROM THE TRAILER. PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENTS AND GLOVES.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO TWO, FIVE GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUMS WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING TOTE IS BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT, AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  A COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, A HISSING SOUND WAS HEARD COMING FROM THE FRONT HALF OF THE TRAILER. column168: A 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS BEING STAGED ON AN ASPHALT LOT AT A TEN DAY TRANSFER FACILITY TO BE LOADED ONTO A TRAILER HEADING FOR THE DESIGNATED DISPOSAL FACILITY.  WHILE SITTING ON THE LOT, THE DRUM CONTAINING GASOLINE STARTED SPILLING OUT OF THE BOTTOM FROM A PINHOLE LEAK.  TWO GALLONS OF GASOLINE HAD SPILLED ONTO THE LOT BEFORE IT WAS DISCOVERED.  THE LEAKING DRUMS WAS IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED INTO A 85-GALLON SALVAGE DRUM AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL PLACED ONTO THE SPILL.  THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT WAS ALSO CONTAINERIZED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 30 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD IN DENTON, TX FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR THE DRUM PICK UP WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

DRIVER ARRIVED TO MAKE DELIVERY, FOUND A SMALL QUANTITY OF LIQUID ON THE FLOOR UNDER THE PALLET THAT THE DRUMS WERE ON. CONSIGNEE WOULD NOT TAKE ANYTHING UNTIL THE LEAKER WAS SECURED AND WOULD NOT GIVE THE DRIVER ANY ASSISTANCE TO ISOLATE IT. THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO PLACE SPILL KIT PADS ONTO THE SPILLAGE. HAZMAT CONTACTED A NEARBY CONTRACTOR AND MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR THE DRIVER TO GO THERE. THE CONTRACTOR OVERPACKED THE LEAKER AND PUT THE PADS THAT THE DRIVER USED INTO THE OVERPACK ALSO. AN EXAMINATION OF THE LEAK AREA INDICATES THAT THE DRUM SUFFERED FORK DAMAGE. THE SHIPMENT THAT HAD BEEN IMMEDIATELY BEHIND THE DAMAGED ONE HAD BEEN PALLETIZED DRUMS OF INK. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE DAMAGED DRUM HAD BEEN TOUCHED BY A FORK THAT PROTRUDED FROM A PALLET DURING UNLOADING OF THE INK SHIPMENT.

AFTER BACKING INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S DOCK, THE DRIVER REMOVED SECURING STRAPS FROM THE SHIPMENT AND SET THE STRAPS' BUCKLES INTO THE TRAILER'S LOGISTIC TRACK. THE CONSIGNEE'S FORK LIFT OPERATOR PICKED UP A PALLET OF DRUMS THAT WAS AGAINST THE WALL AND BEGAN TO BACK OUT WITHOUT SHIFTING THE PALLET AWAY FROM THE WALL. WHEN HE DID SO, ONE DRUM STRUCK A STRAP BUCKLE AND WAS PIERCED. A SPILLAGE OF ABOUT A PINT OF THE MATERIAL'S WETTING AGENT RESULTED. CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL PUT THE DRUM ONTO ITS SIDE TO STOP THE SPILL, THEN FINISHED UNLOADING. THEY KEPT THE DAMAGED DRUM AND GAVE THE DRIVER A CLEAR RECEIPT FOR THE SHIPMENT

DRIVER HAD MADE A DELIVERY OF H/M EARLIER IN THE DAY.  AT THAT TIME, HE NOTED AN ODOR IN THE TRAILER AND BROUGHT IT TO THE CONSIGNEE'S ATTENTION. HOWEVER, THERE WAS NOTHING VISIBLE TO INDICATE ANY LEAKAGE. CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL STATED THAT THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM THEIR FACILITY AND IS NORMAL.  AFTER COMPLETING DELIVERY, THE DRIVER CONTINUED ON HIS WAY. SHORTLY AFTER, HE STOPPED FOR A BREAK AT A ROADSIDE REST AREA.  WHILE THERE, HE NOTED THE CONTINUED PRESENCE OF THE ODOR.  INVESTIGATING THE SOURCE, HE FOUND A SMALL QUANTITY OF LIQUID IMPOUNDED IN THE GROOVES OF THE ALUMINUM TRAILER FLOOR AND NOTIFIED THE CARRIER.  CARRIER'S HAZMAT SPECIALIST IDENTIFIED THE MATERIAL, AS CERTAINED THAT THERE WAS NO LIKELY HOOD OF ITS ESCAPE AND INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO CONTINUE TO A FACILITY WHERE HELP COULD BE SENT.  CARRIER THEN ENGAGED THE SERVICES OF AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR TO HANDLE A CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL OF ANY WASTE GENERATED.

ONE DRUM ARRIVED AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY WITH LIQUID AROUND ITS HEAD. ONE OF TWO BUNGS WAS NOT SECURED TIGHT.  SPILL PADS WERE USED TO ABSORB THE LIQUID.  THE BUNGS WERE RETIGHTENED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

TRAILER ARRIVED AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY FROM A REMOTE FACILITY.  WHEN IT WAS OPENED FOR UNLOADING THERE WAS LIQUID ON THE TRAILER'S FLOOR.  A PALLET OF  PAILS OF CYANIDE SOLUTION WAS LOADED AT THE END OF THE TRAILER AND WAS SUSPECTED OF BEING THE SOURCE OF THE LEAKAGE.  DOCK PERSONNEL SECURED THE TRAILER AND CONTACTED THE CARRIER'S ON CALL HAZMAT SPECIALIST.  GIVEN THE NATURE OF THE SUSPECTED LEAK SOURCE, THE HAZMAT SPECIALIST INSTRUCTED DOCK PERSONNEL TO ISOLATE THE TRAILER AND DENY ENTRY, AND TO AWAIT THE ARRIVAL OF A CONTRACTOR.  CARRIER ENGAGED THE SERVICES OF A CONTRACTOR WHO RESPONDED TO THE FACILITY.  THEY WERE ABLE TO DETERMINE THAT THE PALLET CONTAINING THE H/M HAD A TOTAL OF NINETEEN PAILS ON IT.  SIXTEEN PAILS WERE PROPERLY STACKED AND SECURED.  THREE PAILS WERE SHIPPED LOOSE BUT WERE SET ON TOP OF THE PALLET AND SHRINK WRAPPED TOGETHER BUT WERE NOT OTHERWISE SECURED TO THE PALLET.  THE CONTRACTOR PERFORMED THE NECESSARY CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE.  A MASSACHUSETTS LICENSED SITE PROFESSIONAL WAS RETAINED TO INSPECT THE SITE.

CONTINUED INVESTIGATION REVEALED A LEAKING DRUM OF PAINT IN A DIFFERENT SHIPMENT. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AGAINST A PALLET. THE CARRIER PROVIDED A SALVAGE DRUM FROM ITS STOCK WHICH THE CONTRACTOR USED TO OVERPACK THE LEAKING DRUM.  IT WAS HELD FOR INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

column168: A TRAILER WAS AT THE LOADING DOCK AT A SAFETY-KLEEN DISPOSAL FACILITY. WHEN THE DOORS WERE OPENED, THEY FOUND A 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM HAD BURST ITS LID FROM THE RING CLAMP DUE TO INTERNAL PRESSURE.  THREE GALLONS OF THE BAGHOUSE WASTE CONTAINING TRACE AMOUNTS OF CHROMIUM HAD SPILLED ONTO THE RAILER FLOOR.  THE MATERIAL WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE DRUM AND THE DRUM OVERPACKED INTO AN 85-GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.  THE TRAILER WAS WIPED DOWN TO REMOVE ANY RESIDUAL WASTE.  THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 30 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TREATED AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 5756 ALBA STREET IN LOS ANGELES, CA FOR DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON DRUM INSPECTION PROCEDURES AND THE WASTE STREAM FROM THE GENERATOR WAS REEVALUATED TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON FEBRUARY 24, 2001 OUR PROPANE TRANSPORT WAS IN THE CENTER LANE OF I-75, HEADING NORTH TO MIO, MICHIGAN WITH A FULL LOAD OF PROPANE. SLUSH WAS ACCUMULATING IN THE ROADWAY IN AREAS WITHOUT TRAFFIC. ANOTHER VEHICLE, TRAVELING IN THE LEFT LANE GOT INTO THE SLUSH, LOST CONTROL AND SPUN OUT IN FRONT OF OUR  DRIVER. OUR DRIVER MOVED TO THE RIGHT LANE, TO AVOID HITTING THE OTHER VEHICLE, HOWEVER THE OTHER VEHICLE ALSO ENDED UP IN THE RIGHT LANE AS WELL. THE DRIVER THEN MOVED FURTHER TO THE RIGHT, WHICH PUT HIM ON THE ENTRANCE RAMP LEADING FROM THE SCALES. THE RAMP WAS SLICK WITH ICE, AS THE SCALES WERE CLOSED, AND THERE WAS NO TRAFFIC ON THE RAMP. OUR DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE TRANSPORT AT THAT POINT, AND SLID INTO THE ROADSIDE DITCH, AND ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE. THERE WAS NO LOSS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, HOWEVER IT REQUIRED THE TRANSFER OF PROPANE TO ANOTHER TRAILER, BEFORE EMERGENCY CREWS COULD UPRIGHT THE TRAILER. WHILE THE TRANSFER PROCESS WAS GOING ON, BOTH THE NORTH AND SOUTH BOUND EXPRESSWAY WAS CLOSED, FOR A PERIOD OF FIFTEEN (15) HOURS.

SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING UPON RETURNING FROM SHIPPER'S DOCK.  THE PROTECTIVE COLLAR AROUND LID HAD LOOSENED ALLOWING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID TO LEAK OUT.  SPILL WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT AND PLACED IN OVERPACK FOR DISPOSAL BY WASTE MANAGEMENT TEAM. THE LEAKING PAIL WAS ALSO PLACED IN OVERPACK. column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING GASOLINE INTO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS.  ONE OF THE TRANSFER HOSES CAME UNLATCHED AT THE POINT WHERE THE HOSE INSERTS INTO THE UNDERGROUND TANK.  APPROXIMATELY 166 GALLONS OF MID-GRADE GASOLINE SPILLED ONTO THE TARMAC OF THE GAS STATION AND SUBSEQUENTLY INTO THE STORM SEWER. FROM THERE, THE GASOLINE TRAVERSED INTO A FEEDER CHANNEL OF THE STORM SEWER SYSTEM AND INTO A CREEK IN A NEARBY NATURE PRESERVE.  FIRE DEPARTMENTS FROM THE CITY OF HUBER HEIGHTS AND DAYTON WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE.  THE CITY OF DAYTON FIRE DEPT. HAZMAT CREW WAS ALSO AT THE SCENE ALONG WITH AN INSPECTOR FROM THE OHIO EPA.  ONYX INDUSTRIAL SERVICES, INC. ASSISTED IN THE CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL OF MATERIALS USED IN THE CLEAN UP.  IT WAS LATER DISCOVERED THAT THE FITTING ON THE END OF THE DROP HOSE HAD A DEFECTIVE LATCHING SYSTEM.  THE MANUFACTURER WAS MADE AWARE OF THE PROBLEM.  THE HOSE WAS SENT TO THEM.  THEY CORRECTED THE PROBLEM AND SENT THE HOUSE BACK TO US.  IF YOU NEED FURTHER INFORMATION PLEASE CONTACT US.

column168: DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, THE DTF TRUCKING, INC. DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER. THE WARREN FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE WARREN POLICE DEPARTMENT, THE MICHIGAN DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND THE SHIPPER, HENKEL SURFACE TECHNOLOGIES RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE INCIDENT. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, ONE DAMAGED FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. APPROXIMATELY, FIFTY-FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED AN ASPHALT SURFACE, SURROUNDING DUNNAGE AND A STORM DRAIN. THE WARREN FIRE DEPARTMENT USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT ON THE ASPHALT SURFACE. THE WARREN FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE SHIPPER, HENKEL SURFACE TECHNOLOGIES, SECURED THE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM. THE SECURED FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM AND TRAILER WERE TRANSPORTED TO HENKEL SURFACE TECHNOLOGIES IN WARREN, MICHIGAN FOR ADDITIONAL CLEANUP. MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL OF DETROIT, MICHIGAN RESPONDED TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP AT THE SPILL LOCATION. MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL USED ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO RECOVER THE FREE PRODUCT. MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL USED A SHOVEL TO RECOVER THE MUD FROM THE AFFECTED STORM DRAIN. MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL PLACED THE AFFECTED MUD,DUNNAGE, AND USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL INTO FIVE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL. THE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO AN EIGHTY GALLON OVERPACK FOR DISPOSAL. MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL TRANSPORTED THE FIVE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS AND THE EIGHTY GALLON OVERPACK TO HENKEL SURFACE TECHNOLOGIES IN WARREN, MICHIGAN FOR DISPOSAL COORDINATION. HENKEL SURFACE TECHNOLOGIES USED A COMPOUNDING AGENT TO REMOVE THE FREE PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER. THE USED COMPOUNDING AGENT WAS PLACED INTO THE FIVE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS WITH THE AFFECTED MUD, DUNNAGE AND USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL. DISPOSAL OF THE FIVE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS AND THE EIGHT GALLON OVERPACK IS BEING COORDINATED BY HENKEL SURFACE TECHNOLOGIES. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.

FILE 30470, SHPR: EXXON MOBIL, AWB# BTR 8480378283 BTR. ON 02/09/01 AT 0324, A SPILL WITH AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 207 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE , Wilmington, OHIO 45177. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS CHRISTOPHER CHAPPS AND JEFFEREY KIDDER, AS WELL AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR TAMARA RAMIREZ DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS LEAKING AND EMITTING AN ODOR.  THEY OPENED THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND BEGAN THEIR INSPECTION.  UPON THIS INSPECTION THEY FOUND A 78 LITER METAL CAN WITH A LOOSE BUNG CLOSURE ON TOP WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE AND AN INNER RUBBER SEAL THAT WAS TOO LOOSE FOR THE CLOSURE, INSIDE THIS FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE CAN LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES.  THIS DID NOT CONTAIN ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THEY REPLACED THE CAN BACK INTO THE FIBERBOARD BOX, SEALED IT AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM, AND RETURNED THE SHIPMENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  THIS WAS A 4 PIECE SHIPMENT, ALL WERE RETURNED.  THIS BOX WAS PROPERTY MARKED AND LABELED.  THIS DID HAVE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION OF DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT. THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THIS WAS WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE WHO NOTICED THE ODOR, SHE WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES WITH THIS EMPLOYEE.  NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED. A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. CLEAR OF ACENE 0406.

THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL A GASOLINE POWERED PUMP.  THE ITEM HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY DRAINED OF FUEL PRIOR TO ITS BEING PACKED AND OFFERED TO FEDEX.  THE ITEM LEAKED ITS FUEL IN TRANSIT AND WAS DISCOVERED BY HANDLING PERSONNEL AT THE INBOUND STATION.  THERE WERE 'NO' HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR INVESTIGATION BY THE F.A.A. TELEPHONIC NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO JOHN WILKERSON/FAA/SFO/CAFSO AT 09:25 (CST) ON 02/05/2001.

column168: CUSTOMER (ANDREA HOLCOMB) TRAVELED FROM SAN DIEGO (SAN) TO NASHVILLE (BNA) WHERE HER FLIGHT TOOK AN OPERATIONAL DELAY DUE TO INCLEMENT WEATHER.  AFTER SEVERAL HOURS TRYING TO GET TO HARTFORD (BBL), HER FINAL FLIGHT OPPORTUNITY WAS CANCELED AND SHE WENT TO CLAIM HER BAG. PICKED UP COAST CAD AT 10:15 TUESDAY 2-13-01.  PICKED UP 4 DRUMS AT SITE....>I HAVE TO BACK INTO THE DEALERSHIP TO GET TO THE BODYSHOP, IN DOING SO I BLOCK IN CUSTOMERS CARS, AFTER TWO DRUMS ON THE LIFT A CUSTOMER ASKED ME TO MOVE, I TOLD HIM THAT I WOULD BE ABOUT 10 MIN.  WELL EVERY TWO MIN. HE WOULD ASK OR TELL ME HE HAD TO LEAVE, SO I HURRIED UP AND LOADED THE LAST TWO DRUMS, THEN THE MANAGER CAME OUT AND TOLD ME HE MIGHT HAVE ONE MORE DRUM, SO  I LEFT THE DRUM DOLLY LYING ON ITS WHEELS, WAITING ON HIM, I FINISHED PUTTING MY SHIPPING LABELS ON THE DRUMS AND WRITING MY MANIFEST, THE MANGER TOLD ME HE DID NOT HAVE ANOTHER DRUM SO I PUT MY DRUM BAR IN PLACE AND SHUT THE BACK DOOR.  WENT TO THE OFFICE AND HAD MANIFEST SIGNED, FORGETTING TO FLIP THE DOLLY OVER.  IN DOING SO I LEFT THE DEALERSHIP AT 10:35, MAKE A RIGHT TURN ON TO THE FOURLANE HIGHWAY WENT 1/4 MILE TO TUTTLE RD.  STOPPED AT LIGHT TO MAKE LEFT TURN.  MADE TURN AT LIGHT WENT ABOUT 1/2 MILE STOPPED AT R/R WHEN A MOTORIST FLAGGED ME SOMETHING WAS WRONG AT THE BACK OF MY TRAILER, THAT MUST HAVE BEEN WHEN DRUM DOLLY WENT FORWARD AND HIT DRUM PUTTING A 1 INCH HOLE IN DRUM ABOUT 4 INCH ABOVE FLOOR, WENT OVER R/R AND PULLED INTO THE MED OF THE ROAD.  FLASHERS ON, AT BACK OF TRAILER SAW SPILLAGE, GRABBED MY MASK OUT OF SIDE BOX, OPENED BACK DOOR SAW HOLE IN DRUM AND KNEW WHAT HAD HAPPENED.  LAYED DRUM ON ITS SIDE, PUT SOME PUTTY IN THE HOLE TO DETAIN SPILL TILL I COULD OPEN OVERPACK DRUM.  OPENED OVERPACK, PUT OVERPACK DRUM OVER LEAKING DRUM, TOOK DRUM FLIP BAR AND STOOD DRUM UP, LID AND RING AND 7/8 WRENCH IT WAS DONE, THEN THE FIRE DEPT, SHOWED UP AND THE SARASOTA POLICE, THEN I TOOK FLOOR DRY AND COVERED SPILL IN TRAILER AND ON THE ASPHALT, THEN I WENT TO THE CAB OF TRUCK AND CALLED DAVE HEMMING..ESTIMATED DURATION OF TIME ABOUT 2-3 MIN OF SPILLAGE.  SPILLAGE TIME - 10:30 TO 10:41 ABOUT 20-25 GALS OF PRODUCT. (EXACT LOCATION - 200 BLOCK OF TUTTLE RD.  SARASOTA, FLA.)  FIRE DEPT.  CHECKED THE SPILL SAW I HAD IT DETAINED, SO WE STOOD AROUND WAITING ON THE LOCAL EPA TO SHOW UP. WHEN HE GOT THEIR, HE LET THE FIRE DEPT. GO THEN HE TOLD ME TO PUT SOME MORE FLOOR DRY DOWN ON THE ASPHALT,  I BROOMED IT INTO THE PAVEMENT AND HE HELPED ME CLEAN IT UP INTO A 5 GAL BUCKET WHICH I PUT IN THE TRAILER AND I LEFT, AT 1:00PM. TWO HOURS LATER I GOT TO FREEHOLD IN BARTOW, FLA. OFFLOADED 37 DRUMS, CLEANED INTERIOR OF TRAILER AND TOOK THE RAGS AND THE FLOOR DRY AND THE FLOORDRY FROM THE SPILL SITE AND PUT IN THE 85 GAL OVEPACK DRUM. GOT TO BARTOW AT 3:00 LEFT AT 5:30 GOT HOME AT 7:00PM 1/2 POST=7:30 NO ONE GAVE ME ANY NAMES OR #, S OR ANYONE TO CONTACT..WHEN EPA LEFT HE SAID TO HAVE A NICE DAY

column168: ADVISED OF U.S. POSTAL SACK THAT SMELLED OF KEROSENE AT APPROXIMATELY 1220 ON 2/20/01.  DETERMINED THIS MAIL CAME VIA TRUCK FROM THE U.S. POST OFFICE LOCATED IN THE DFW INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT TO THE AMERICAN AIRLINES 1E MAIL FACILITY AND HAD NOT YET BEEN TRANSPORTED BY AIR.  DURING THE SORTING PROCESS, AA EMPLOYEES NOTICED A STRONG ODOR OF KEROSENE AND CALLED FOR AN ENVIRONMENTAL CO-ORDINATOR.  THE POSTAL SERVICE INSPECTOR WAS CALLED TO OPEN THE PACKAGE.  A POSTAL RUNNER ARRIVED AND STATED HE WOULD TAKE THE CONTAMINATED PACKAGE BACK TO THE POST OFFICE FOR INSPECTION BY THE PROPER AUTHORITIES.  THE GOLD MAIL SACK WAS NOT WET BUT SMELLED OF KEROSENE.  THE RUNNER DID OPEN THE SACK AND FOUND THE OFFENDING PACKAGE THAT WAS STAINED AND THE SOURCE OF THE SMELL.  THE POSTAL RUNNER ALSO TOOK ONE OTHER BOX THAT WAS CONTAMINATED BY THE FIRST BOX.  CALLED THE U.S. POSTAL INSPECTOR JESSIE HALL AT 972-456-2116 FOR VERIFICATION OF THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX BUT WAS UNABLE TO REACH - LMTC.  BY NOTING THE ADDRESSES ON THE BOX, WE  WERE ABLE TO CALL THE SHIPPER WHO IDENTIFIED THE PRODUCT AS A "GALIEO THERMOMETER" THEY WERE SENDING BACK TO THE MANUFACTURER.  IT CONTAINED PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S.  THE MANUFACTURER, G.W. SCHLEIDT, SENT US AN MSDS.

column168: WE HAD A SHIPMENT OF 22 DRUMS OF PAINT COME IN FROM NBM TONIGHT.  WHEN THE DSR DON ELLIOTT GOT TO NKX HE FOUND PAINT RUNNING OUT OF HIS TRAILER.  WE UNLOADED THE TRAILER ALL DRUMS WERE ON SKIDS FROM THE SHIPPER.  WE FOUND ONE DRUM THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE DRUM BOTTOM WAS IN BAD SHAPE AND LOOKED LIKE IT WAS A USED DRUM THAT HAD BEEN REDONE. THERE WAS A CREASE ON THE BOTTOM AND THAT IS WERE THE DRUM HAD STARTED TO LEAK IT CLEARLY LOOKS LIKE PACKAGE FAILURE.  THIS SPILL TOOK TWO RECOVERY DRUM ONE FOR THE DRUM AND ONE TO PUT THE STAY DRY THAT WAS USED TO CLEAN OUT THE SPILL ALL OF THIS HAS BEEN HELD AT NKX OS&D.

THE SEQUENCE OF EVENTS REPORTED BY STEVE ARE AS FOLLOWS.  THE ENGLAND DRIVER WAS GOING UP THE BLUE MOUNTAIN PASS (CABBAGE HILL) VERY SIMILAR TO THE GRAPEVINE.  THE BAROMETRIC PRESSURE FORCED SOME PARAQUAT OUT OF THE TOP OF ONE OF THE 20 TOTES.  THE REASON DISCOVERED HOW THE POISON WAS RELEASED WAS DUE TO THE FACT THAT SOMEONE PRIOR TO SHIPPING REPLACED A TOP DISPENSING VALVE WITH AN UNAUTHORIZED VALVE.  AS A RESULT THE IMPROPER VALVE WAS OPEN AND ALLOWED THE SIPHON TO TAKE PLACE AS THE TRAILER WAS PULLED UP THE PASS. THE DRIVER WAS UNAWARE OF THE SPILL.  A CITIZEN CALLED THE STATE PATROL. THE STATE PATROL PULLED OVER THE DRIVER AND LOOKED AT THEIR FREIGHT BILLS. THE STATE PATROL CALLED THE ONTARIO FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE I-84 FREEWAY WAS SHUT DOWN FOR APPROX. 4 HOURS.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT LOOKED AT THE CHEMICAL AND CALLED STEVE RITCH ENVIRONMENTAL.  STEVE REQUESTED LINEHAUL TO HAVE A CLEAN ENGLAND TRAILER PULLED TO THE ODOT SAND SHED (MILE POST 268 WHERE THEY COULD SWING THE FREIGHT.  PASCO PULLED OUT A CLEAN ENGLAND EMPTY TRAILER TO THE SITE.  STEVE AND HIS CREW HAD ON FULL PPE.  THEY PLACED THE DRY FREIGHT INTO THE CLEAN ENGLAND TRAILER.   ANY WET OR CONTAMINATED FREIGHT WAS PLACED ON PLASTIC SHEETING ON THE GROUND.  AFTER THE ORIGINAL WET TRAILER WAS EMPTIED SOMEONE PULLED IT TO A TRUCK WASH TO BE DECONTAMINATED.  ALL THE RINSE WATER WAS CAPTURED IN 55 GALLON DRUMS, CURRENTLY SITTING IN BAKER CITY. AFTER THE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED, THERE WAS A GUARD SERVICE HIRED FOR THE ODOT SAND SHED TO PROTECT THE PUBLIC FROM THE POISON.  THE SERVICE WAS PAID 45.00/HR FOR APPROX. 40 HOURS.  THERE WAS HIGH WINDS THAT KEPT BLOWING OVER THE FREIGHT THAT WAS STACKED ON THE GROUND.  FOR SAFETY REASONS ALL THE FREIGHT WAS MOVED TO A SECURED AND PROTECTED YARD IN BAKER CITY.  SINCE THE CLEAN TRAILER WAS NOW CONTAMINATED FROM TAIL LOADING ON THE WET FREIGHT, ENGLAND HAD TO PULL ANOTHER CLEAN EMPTY TO BAKER CITY.  (NOTE:  STEVE RITCH ALSO OWNS A TOWING SERVICE AND ENGLAND HAS AN ACCOUNT WITH HIM)  STEVE REPORTED TO THE DEQ AND THE OREGON HEALTH DEPARTMENT THAT THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS FROM THE WRONG VALVE BEING INSTALLED ON ONE OF THE TOTES.  JOHN KURK WAS THE PERSON IN CHARGE FROM THE ONTARIO FIRE DEPARTMENT.  HE HAS 4/5 ROLLS OF PHOTO TAKEN ON THE SCENE.  STEVE ALSO HAS APPROX. 4/5 ROLLS OF 35 MM PHOTOS TAKEN SO FAR.  I HAVE COPIES OF A FEW KEY SHOTS SHOWING THE B/O VALVE AND THE DAMAGE TO OTHER FREIGHT AND EQUIPMENT.  STEVE STATES HE HAS MANY PHONE HOURS LOGGED WITH OUR LINEHAUL DEPARTMENT, SEVERAL HOURS WITH OREGON DEQ MIKE RENZ, AND ADDITIONAL HOURS TO BE CHARGED TALKING WITH OREGON HEALTH DEPARTMENT, ONTARIO FIRE DEPARTMENT INCLUDING THE MANUFACTURE CENJENTA (DON PAULSON-CHEMIST) THE SHIPPER AGRILIANCE WAS ALSO CONTACTED AND THEY REQUESTED ALL 20 TOTES BE DELIVERED BACK TO THEIR WAREHOUSE.  THEY WERE SCHEDULED ON ENGLAND FOR 2 - 22 - 01 DELIVERY.  THE LEAKING TOTE VALVE AND THE OTHER GOOD VALVES PHOTOS WILL BE INCLUDED IN STEVE'S FINAL REPORT. I HAVE CONTACTE

column168: TANK CAR TEAX 3413, LD LP GAS WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING VAPORS HEAVILY FROM THE DOME AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN BALDWIN, FL.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ON THE SOUTH END.  HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER EG COOK RESPONDED AND DISCOVERED THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (SRV) WAS FROSTED UP & LIQUID PRODUCT WAS BUBBLING UP FROM THE VALVE EGC CHECKED THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR.  THE PRESSURE READING WAS 280 PSIG.  CSXT ATTEMPTED TO NOTIFY THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC BUT THE SHIPPER OF THE CAR WAS NOT LISTED WITH CHEMTREC.  THE JACKSONVILLE, FL FIRE DEPT HAZMAT TEAM WAS REQUESTED AND THEY RESPONDED... EGC TALKED TO BRYAN WILKIN, COAST ENERGY GROUP AND REQUESTED A TANKER TRUCK TO UNLOAD SOME PRODUCT.  A CONTRACTOR MONITORED FOR FLAMMABLE CONDITIONS.  NO FLAMMABILITY HAZARD WAS DETECTED.  SOME PRODUCT WAS BLED FROM THE VAPOR VALVE WHILE THE F.D. APPLIED A WATER FOG. THE PRESSURE DROPPED TO 240 PSIG AND THE LIQUID LEAK AT THE SERV STOPPED A TOTAL OF 4500 GALS OF PRODUCT WAS OFFLOADED INTO 2 "BOBTAIL" TANKER TRUCKS FROM MOBIL GAS CO OF JACKSONVILLE, FL, RESUTLING IN A 22 INCH OUTAGE.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED, THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED.  MR BRYAN WILKINS ADVISED CAR WAS LOADED BY EXXON MOBILE IN JAY, FL.

column168: FILE 3063 D, SHIPPER: MACINTYRE FUEL INC, AWB# BTV 3944768786 ELZ.  ON 02/20/01 AT 0104 A ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 207 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZMAT TECHNICIANS DONALD OSBORNE AND TIMOTHY HINES DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGING. THE REMOVED THIS PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN 3 INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES.  THEY OPENED THESE AND FOUND THEM TO CONTAIN 2 X 1L GLASS BOTTLES, GASOLINE EACH.  ALSO EACH INNER BOX CONTAINED FIBERBOARD DIVIDERS TO SECURE THE INNER BOTTLES.  THE SHIPMENT DID NOT CONTAIN ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  IT WAS OUNCES DUE TO LOOSE CLOSURE AND IMPROPER ORIENTATION.  THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS INTO THE BOXES INTO THE BOX, RESEALED THEM, AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED IT ONTO IT'S DESTINATION.  THIS PACKAGE WAS PROPERTY MARKED, LABELED AND HAD THE APPROPRIATE HAZ CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING IT.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR, SHE WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES REPORTED WITH THIS EMPLOYEE.  NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE AT ILN.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0110.

column168: FILE 3054 D, SHIPPER: UNITED SPRAY SYSTEMS.  AWB# MSP 58481601752 ALB.  ON 02/20/01 AT 1120 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING D OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZMAT TECHNICIAN CECELIA HICKEY AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR BENJAMIN TAYLOR DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A WHITE FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THIS FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INSPECTION.  UPON THIS INSPECTION THEY FOUND THIS TO CONTAIN THE FOLLOWING REGULATED ITEM:  2 X 1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES, PLASTIC FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES, WITH TAPE AROUND THEM, "ORROZAP RESIDUAL INSECT SPRAY 2 EC. EACH BOTTLE WAS PACKED INSIDE A PLASTIC BAG, NEITHER OF WHICH HAD ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  ONE OF THESE BOTTLES HAD A LOOSE CLOSURE, DESPITE THE TAPE AROUND IT, CAUSING THE LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 5 OUNCES.  THIS ALSO PRODUCED A "SKUNK LIKE" ODOR.  THESE ITEMS WERE REPLACED INTO THEIR PLASTIC BAGS, PLACED BACK INTO THE FIBERBOARD BOX, RESEALED THE BOX, AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THIS DRUM WAS PLACED INTO THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNTIL PROPER CERTIFICATION COULD BE OBTAINED TO MOVE THIS SHIPMENT.  BENJAMIN CALLED THE SHIPPER AND OBTAINED AN MSDS ON THIS SHIPMENT.  ACCORDING TO THIS MSDS THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME FOR THIS PRODUCT IS "ORGANOPHOSPHOROUS PESTICIDE, LIQUID, TOXIC, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S. (CONTAINS: DIMETHOATE, CYCLOHEXANONE)".  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THERE WERE 2 EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT IT WAS, GIVEN A COPY OF THE MSDS, AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED NO CHANGES WERE REPORTED.  A COPY OF THE MSDS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE AT ILN. CLEAR OF SCENE 1139.

FILE: 3055 D, SHIPPER: HAZARDOUS GLASS IND, AWB#TOP 329416425 PUB.  ON 02/23/01 AT 0105 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING C OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZMAT TECHNICIAN WILLIAM HENDERSON DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A WHITE FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  HE REMOVED THIS FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION HE FOUND THIS BOX TO CONTAIN: 12 X 19 OUNCE METAL AEROSOL CANS.  "BINSWANGER GLASS CLEANER-CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE."  ONE OF THESE CANS HAD A 1/4 INCH SPILL JUST ABOVE THE BOTTOM CHIME.  THIS CAUSED IT TO LEAK IT'S ENTIRE CONTENTS. THIS DID NOT CONTAIN ABSORBENT MATERIAL, NOR DID IT HAVE ANY MEANS TO SEPARATE OR SECURE THESE CANS INSIDE THIS BOX.  HE REPLACED THE CANS INTO THE BOX, RESEALED IT, AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE BAGGED SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION VIA GROUND.  THIS BOX WAS PROPERTY MARKED, LABELED BUT DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING IT.  THIS DID ARRIVE/DEPART ILN VIA GROUND.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THERE WERE 3 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, AND NO CHANGES WERE REPORTED WITH THESE EMPLOYEES.  NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE ILN. CLEAR OF SCENE 0128.

MGR. WILDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM RMCC THAT A TANK CAR IN CLINTON, IOWA WAS LEAKING AND VENTING.  Sr. MTO MIKE LITTRELL HAD THE CAR MOVED TO THE RIP TRACK WHERE THE CAR WOULD BE ISOLATED.  UPON INSPECTION, MGR.  WILDER FOUND THAT THE RUPTURE DISK HAD BLOWN AND THAT A MANWAY COVER BOLT WAS MISSING FROM THE 10" QUICK FILE HOLE.  MGR. WILDER REPAIRED THE RUPTURE DISK AND TALKED TO THE SHIPPER, ATOFINA CHEMICAL INC, CARL HAMBLIN ABOUT THE MANWAY COVER. MR HAMBLIN ADVISED THAT RESCAR WOULD REPAIR THE MANWAY COVER BOLT THE NEXT MORNING AT 9 AM.  MGR. WILDER ALSO INSTRUCTED MR. HAMBLIN TO HAVE RESCAR CLEAN THE SIDE OF THE CAR WHERE PRODUCT HAD SPILLED. NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND AND NO WATERWAYS OR DRAINS WERE EFFECTED BY THIS SPILL.

column42: PHOSPHORUS, WHITE OR YELLOW DRY OR UNDER WATER OR IN SOLUTION
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1100 MST ON 2/26/01, TRAIN LIF33 26 WHILE SETTING OUT CARS AT ASTARIS ELEMENTAL PHOSPHORUS PLANT DERAILED 4 LOADS OF COKE AND 6 EMPTY OR RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED PHOSPHORUS TANK CARS.  AT 1140 MST, ED BANKS, MEFO WAS CALLED BY HARRY RODAGOUGH, MCTS AND ASKED TO GO TO THE SITE AND ASSESS THE SITUATION.  WHEN MR. BANKS ARRIVED, THERE WERE THREE PHOSPHORUS TANK CARS DERAILED ON THEIR SIDES AND THREE DERAILED AND LEANING.  THERE WERE NO LEAKS AT THE TIME.  A SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION AT 1500 MST FOUND THAT ACFX 73025, DERAILED ON ITS SIDE, HAD BEGUN TO SEEP PRODUCT FROM THE FLANGES OF THE LONG STANDPIPE AND THE THERMOMETER WELL.  MR. BANKS HAD PLANT PERSONNEL TIGHTEN THE FLANGE NUTS AS BEST THEY COULD AND PLACE A COLLECTION BUCKET UNDER THE FLANGES.  THE SEEPAGE NEVER EXCEEDED MORE THAN 4 OR 5 DROPS PER MINUTE AND MR. BANKS ESTIMATES LESS THAN ONE CUP OF LIQUID ACTUALLY HIT THE GROUND.  THE SEEPAGE WAS CAUSED BY HEAD PRESSURE OF THE PRODUCT AGAINST THE GASKETS FOR AN EXTENDED PERIOD OF TIME.  THE GASKETS ARE NORMALLY DRY.  THE SEEPAGE STOPPED AFTER DARK BECAUSE OF COLD TEMPERATURE FREEZING UP THE LEAK, BUT BEGAN AGAIN AT THE SAME RATE ABOUT 1000 MST ON 2/27/01 AFTER THE SUN WARMED THE FLANGES. THE COLLECTION BUCKET REMAINED IN PLACE UNTIL ABOUT 1500 WHEN THE CAR WAS ROLLED UPRIGHT REMOVING THE PRESSURE FROM THE FLANGES. LESS THAN ONE PINT HAD BEEN COLLECTED AND WAS DISPOSED OF BY PLANT PERSONNEL.

A SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE, MR. JIM COFARO FROM KOPPER'S INDUSTRIES IN CHICAGO REPORTED TO MS. BARB SCHRAM, TEAM LEADER, NCSC THAT TANKCAR UTLX 641997 HAD INADVERTENTLY BEEN PICKED UP AND PUT IN TRANSPORTATION BY THE BRC RAILROAD IN CHICAGO.  THE CAR HAD BEEN UNDERGOING AN INSPECTION, AND THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HAD BEEN REMOVED FOR RECERTIFICATION, AND PUT IN TRANSPORTATION BY THE BRC RAILROAD IN CHICAGO.  THE CAR HAD BEEN UNDERGOING AN INSPECTION, AND THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HAD BEEN REMOVED FOR RECERTIFICATION, AND A BLIND FLANGE PLATE HAD BEEN PLACED OVER THE SRV HOLE BUT WAS UNSECURED.  MR. COFARO WAS CONCERNED THAT DESPITE ASSURANCES FROM THE BRC THAT THEY WOULD SET THE CAR OUT AND HAVE AN SRV APPLIED TO THE CAR, HE SUSPECTED THAT THE BRC MAY NOT HAVE COMPLETED THESE REPAIRS.  THE CAR HAD BEEN INTERCHANGED TO THE UP AND WAS ON TRAIN MCHNP 21, DESTINATION NORTH PLATTE.  MS SCHRAM NOTIFIED UP'S  RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER AND RMCC NOTIFIED MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY. MR. REIMERS ASKED THAT THE CAR BE INSPECTED WHEN THE TRAIN STOPPED IN MARSHALLTOWN, IA FOR A CREW CHANGE.  THE MECHANIC IN CHARGE AND MIKE ERWIN, MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS INSPECTED THE CAR AND TIGHTENED WHAT WAS DESCRIBED AS THE "SAFETY RELIEF VALVE" WHERE CREOSOTE WAS LEAKING. MR. REIMERS APPROVED THE  MOVEMENT OF THE CAR TO FREMONT, NE WHERE HE COULD PERSONALLY INSPECT THE CAR.  WHEN MR. REIMERS INSPECTED THE CAR IN FREMONT, HE DISCOVERED THAT THE CAR WAS MISSING THE SRV AND WHAT THE MIC HAD TIGHTENED WAS THE BLIND FLANGE ON THE SRV OPENING. APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM THE OPENING PRIOR TO THE BLIND FLANGE BEING TIGHTENED.  ALL OF THE CREOSOTE WAS CONTAINED ON TOP OF THE CAR AND NONE REACHED THE GROUND.  THE CAR WAS PLACED IN BAD ORDER STATUS AND A MOBILE UTLX REPAIR TRUCK PLACE AN SRV ON THE CAR ON MARCH 9. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: MARTINEZ, GENERAL YARD MASTER, REPORT TANKCAR GATX 26042, LOCATED IN THE WEST COLTON YARD ON TRACK ONE, BOWL 34, WAS LEAKING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE ON THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR.  MR. MARTINEZ STATED THE PRODUCT TRICKLED DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANKCAR AND ONTO THE GROUND.  MITCH DUGGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  HE ALSO REQUESTED STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS BE MADE BY RMCC.  MR. DUGGER DETERMINED THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY RUPTURE DISK FAILURE AND THE DISC WOULD NEED TO BE REPLACED. column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT PHOENIX, AZ.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED THE PHOENIX YARDMASTER AND DEVELOPED THE ABOVE TANK CAR WAS IN YARD  #3 AND WAS NOTICED DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET BY THE CAR DEPARTMENT AS THEY WERE INSPECTING THE TRAIN.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED ERI, AND HAD THEM RESPOND TO AFFECT REPAIRS.  UPON ERI'S ARRIVAL, DEVELOPED THE PRODUCT WAS BY PASSING THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP, WHICH WAS ONLY HAND TIGHT, AT A RATE OF SEVERAL DROPS PER MINUTE.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS SEATED AND IN THE CLOSED POSITION.  ERI REMOVED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP, TEFLON TAPED THE NOZZLE THREADS,  REINSTALLED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP, AND PROPERLY TIGHTENED IT WITH THE USE OF A 36 INCH PIPE WRENCH, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  IT APPEARS THE PRODUCT IS BY PASSING A DEFECTIVE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, AND DUE TO AN IMPROPERLY TIGHTENED CAP, THE PRODUCT WAS ALLOWED TO DISCHARGE FROM THE CAR.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, WHO WAS ADVISED TO HAVE THE CAR SHOPPED FOR REPAIRS UPON RETURN TO TEXAS. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

W.M. SEABAUGH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY UPRR CONTACTED BY UPRR RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER ADVISED THAT TANK CAR UTLX 48063 WAS REPORTED LEAKING WHILE LOCATED IN UPRR YARD AT N. LITTLE ROCK, AR, SEABAUGH RESPONDED TO SCENE WHERE HE DISCOVERED VACUUM RELIEF/BRAKER VENTING VAPORS INTO ATMOSPHERE.  SEABAUGH WAS ABLE TO RESEAT VACUUM RELIEF/BREAKER WHICH STOPPED RELEASE OF CHEMICAL VAPOR.  SEABAUGH COMMUNICATED THAT TANK CAR WAS SECURE TO UPRR CAR DEPARTMENT AT N. LITTLE ROCK AND TO RMCC.  SEABAUGH ALSO REQUESTED SHIPPER BE ADVISED VIA CHEMTREC. SEABAUGH SECURED TANK CAR AT 11:43HRS 02/18/2001.  DURING INSPECTION SEABAUGH REMOVED (INTACT) SEAL LOCATED ON PROTECTIVE HOUSING TOP VALVE COVER # SOUTHERN RAILWAY 10374286.

AT ABOUT 1100 HOURS OF FRIDAY, 2/16/01, UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED BY YARD PERSONNEL AT THE LIVONIA, LOUISIANA YARD, THAT TANK CAR ACFX 200277, ON BOWL TRACK 25 WAS LEAKING LIQUID FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  INSPECTION BY ROBINSON REVEALED THAT LIQUID WAS STREAMING DOWN BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR FROM BENEATH THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING FOR THE AIR AND LIQUID VALVES.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ONTO TRACK 105 WITH OUT INCIDENT TO TAKE ADVANTAGE OF DRIP PANS. A SOUTH WEST WIND DID RESULT IN SOME OF THE LIQUID FALLING ONTO THE BALLAST AT THIS LOCATION AS WELL. ROBINSON CONTACTED EAGLE CONSTRUCTION AND ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO ASSIST WITH STOPPING THE LEAK AND CLEANING UP THE SPILLAGE.  UNION PACIFIC RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER CONTACTED THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENV, QUALITY, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, CHEMTREC AND AIR PRODUCTS CHEMICALS, THE SHIPPER. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT A STREAM OF LIQUID WAS SPRAYING OUT FROM BETWEEN THE LIQUID VALVE FLANGE AND THE TANK CAR.  THE NUTS ON THE MOUNTING STUDS WERE TIGHTENED AND THIS STOPPED THE LEAK.  A GAGE WAS PLACED ON THE AIR VALVE AND THIS INDICATED 4 PSI.  THE VAPOR PRESSURE WAS RELEASED AND THE LIQUID VALVE DISMOUNTED.  THIS REVEALED AN OLD INEFFECTIVE GASKET WHICH WAS REPLACED.  THE LIQUID VALVE WAS REINSTALLED AND THE CAR WAS SECURED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  MR. DAVE WILLIAMS OF THE LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENV. QUALITY RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  WITH HIS PERMISSION THE SPILLED CYCLOHEXYLAMAINE, WHICH HAD BEEN DILUTED BY A SIGNIFICANT RAIN SHOWER THAT PASSED THROUGH IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED, WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH ACETIC ACID.

FRA INSPECTOR BRUCE MARRIOTT, WHILE CONDUCTING COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT MONTPELIER IDAHO, OBSERVED LEAKING TANKCAR JRSX10181.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE SHIPPER HAD FAILED TO APPLY THE ONE INCH PIPE CAP ON THE AIR VALVE, LEAVING THE CAR OPEN.  MGR. RODABOUGH MADE REPAIR BY SIMPLY APPLYING THE CAP WHICH WAS STILL ON THE CAR ATTACHED BY THE CHAIN.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: TIM O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MGR. CTS WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REGARDING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN SETTEGAST YARD.  MR O'BRIEN RESPONDED AND FOUND THE FRANGIBLE DISC ON THE CAR HAD RUPTURED.  AFTER CONFERRING WITH THE SHIPPER, MR. O'BRIEN REPLACED THE RUPTURED DISC WITH A NEW 165# DISC.  THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE ALSO TIGHTENED AS THEY WERE LOOSE.  THE AREA WHERE PRODUCT HAD SPILLED ON THE TANKCAR WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH VINEGAR.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

RICK SLOANE, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED KATHY DEDMORE, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS NOTIFIED HIM THAT TANKCAR ACFX 79723 WAS FOUND LEAKING INSIDE THE EUGENE YARD.  THE TANKCAR HAD SPLASHED METHANOL FROM THE TOP DURING SWITCHING MOVEMENT.  THE TANKCAR WAS ISOLATED ON THE OLD HUMP LEAD UNTIL SLOANE ARRIVED ON SCENE.  THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED TO THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR, NOT ON THE GROUND.  MR. SLOANE INSPECTED THE TANKCAR AND FOUND THAT THE GASKET WAS OUT OF PLACE AND ONE MANWAY COVER BOLT WAS LOOSE.  MR. SLOANE REPAIRED THE TANKCAR AND RELEASED IT  FOR DELIVERY TO BORDEN CHEMICAL IN SPRINGFIELD, OR.  MR. SLOANE REQUESTED RMCC CONTACT CHEMTREC TO MAKE A COURTESY NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER.  THE REQUESTED NOTIFICATION WAS MADE AND SPILL NUMBER 02092001035 WAS ASSIGNED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: TWO USED CHAIN SAWS INSIDE PLASTIC CARRYING CASES, ONE WITH APPROXIMATELY 1/4 OF A TANK OF GAS ARRIVED JFK ON AA FLT 1443 ON 6 FEB. WHILE TRANSFERRING ITEMS TO OUTBOUND AA FLT 1165 ON 6 FEB AN EMPLOYEE DETECTED A GASOLINE ODOR FROM ONE OF THE CASES. THE TWO CASES WERE CONFISCATED AND THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED.THE ORIGIN STATION (BDA) WAS CONTACTED FOR FOLLOW UP WITH THOSE INVOLVED WITH THE ACCEPTANCE AND LOADING OF THE 2 PIECES. THE INCIDENT IS NOW BEING USED DURING LOCAL TRAINING REGARDING PROPER HANDLING OF DANGEROUS GOODS.

column168: UTLX 48644 WAS REPORTED LEAKING AT EAGLE PASS, TEXAS.  INSPECTION REVEALED THE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE LEAKING AND ONE BOLT BROKEN OFF.  THE CAR WAS PLUGGED WITH PLUG AND PATCH MATERIAL UNTIL THE CAR COULD BE TRANSFERRED INTO TRUCKS THE FOLLOWING DAY.
PALLET WAS SITTING IN THE OS&D BAY OF THE DOCK, AND THE MATERIAL WAS HIT AND PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT. THE DAMAGE WAS DISCOVERED BY ANTHONY DAVIS. HE CLEARED THE SPILL

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY MTO BILL DAWSON, REPORTING AN OIL SPILL IN COMPTON. DEVELOPED SOMEONE FROM THE BLUE LINE STATION AT COMPTON HAD NOTED THE ABOVE TANK CAR LEAKING AS IT PASSED THE STATION PLATFORM AND NOTIFIED MTO DAWSON. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE DOLORES YARD AND INSPECTED THE INBOUND OWPDO2-5 AND FOUND THE ABOVE CAR WITH THE 10 INCH TOP MOUNTED FLEX HOSE TORN OFF. THE RESIDUE OIL IN THE LINE WAS COVERING THE END OF THE ABOVE CAR, AS WELL AS THE ADJACENT CAR, GATX 23667. INTERVIEW WITH THE TRAIN CREW DEVELOPED NO UNUSUAL EVENTS WHILE THEY HAD THE TRAIN. DEVELOPED THROUGH RMCC THAT THIS TRAIN HAD REPORTED A PULL A APART AROUND 2AM WHILE IN SANTA MARGARITA, WHICH IS WHERE THE TRAIN ORGINATES. RMCC WAS REQUESTED TO MAKE STATE AND COUNTY NOTIFICATIONS IN AN EFFORT TO LOCATE THE AREA WHERE THE TRAIN PULLED APART FOR REMEDIATION PURPOSES.

DURING A DELIVERY - THE NOZZLE ON THE TANKER TRUCK WOULD NOT SHUT OFF IMMEDIATELY CAUSING A TANK TO OVERFLOW.

column168: OUR VEHICLE HAD JUST FINISHED MAKING A 50 GALLON HEATING OIL DELIVERY TO 449 E COSGROVE ST. PHILA, PA AND WAS REELING IN HIS DELIVERY HOSE. AS THE DRIVER WAS PLACING THE DELIVERY HOSE NOZZLE BACK INTO THE TRUCK, IT SLIPPED OUT OF HIS HANDS AND FELL TO THE GROUND LANDING ON THE SHUT OFF LATCH. THE LATCH OPENED APPOX 1/2 TURN AND ALLOWED APPOX 2 GALLONS OF HEATING OIL TO SPILL OUT ONTO THE CENTER OF THE STREET. BECAUSE STREET WAS ON A SLIGHT ANGLE. THE FUEL OIL ROLLED OVER TO THE SIDE CURB TRAVELING  A FEW FEET ALONG THE CURB.THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SECURED THE NOZZLE AND COVERED THE SPILL WITH ABOUT 20 POUNDS OF OIL ABSORBANT. THE FUEL NEVER CAME CLOSE TO ENTERING ANY WATER WAY OR SEWER. THE TRUCK WAS BROUGHT BACK TO 2700 ROBERTS AVE PHILA, PA TO HAVE THE DELIVERY NOZZLE INSPECTED FOR ANY DEFECTS.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: CONTAINER MOLU2490983 LOADED ON BOARD THE HYUNDAI INNOVATOR 141W FROM VANCOUVER CANADA. THE ORIGINAL PLACE OF RECEIPT WAS ONTARIO, CANADA. THE CONTAINER WAS DESTINED FOR HONG KONG ON 02-09-2001 DIANA JACKSON (MOL OPERATIONS MANAGER) WAS NOTIFIED CONTAINER MOLU2490983 SAID TO CONTAIN A HAZARDOUS COMMODITY WAS LEAKING. THE CONTAINER WAS DISCHARGED FROM THE VESSEL AT THE NEXT PORT OF CALL PORTLAND, OREGON. THE CONTAINER WAS DISCHARGED FROM THE VESSEL BY THE AUTHORITY OF U.S. CUSTOMS INSPECTOR DAVE FERGISON. THE CONTAINER WAS CONSIDERED AS AN EMERGENCY OFF LOAD AND IMMEDIATELY TURNED OVER TO FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL AND THE U.S. COAST GUARD. THE ABOVE REFERENCED CONTAINER WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING THOUGH THE DOOR SEALS AND FLOOR OF CONTAINER MOLU2490983. IT WAS NOTED THE SHIP'S DECK AND HATCH COVER, SUBJACENT TO THE CONTAINER, TO BE COVERED IN LIQUID. THE SUBJECT CONTAINER WAS DISCHARGED FROM THE VESSEL AT 1615 HOURS WITH USCG AND LOCAL FIRE STATION IN ATTENDANCE. FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL WRAPPED THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER IN A HEAVY GAUGE POLY SHEET AND REMOVED AS MUCH LIQUID VARNISH FROM THE DECK AND HATCH COVER AS POSSIBLE. USCG AND FIRE BUREAU REQUIRED THE TRANSLOAD OF THE GOODS FROM WITHIN THE CONTAINER AND THE SEGREGATION OF LEAKING DRUMS. THE CONTAINER WAS SET OVER SHEETS OF POLY, WITHIN THE OPEN YARD AT THE TERMINAL IN AN AREA DESIGNATED FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. 35 STEEL DRUMS SAID TO CONTAIN TEXTURE WET INK VARNISH WERE FOUND STOWED ON LUMBER PALLET FOUR (4) DRUMS ACROSS AND EIGHT (8) DRUMS DEEP. AN ADDITIONAL THREE (3) DRUMS WERE SET ON A LUMBER PALLET OVER STEEL DRUMS IN-WAY OF THE FORWARD SECTION OF THE CONTAINER. THE DRUMS WERE APPARENTLY SECURED BY A 3/4" STEEL TENSION BAND SET TAUT AROUND THEM. IN ADDITION A 2"X4" LUMBER CROSS BRACE WAS SET ABAFT THESE DRUMS. THE DRUMS IN WAY OF THE LOWER TIER WERE FUND TO BE SECURED BY TENSION BAND AND THE FAT END OF STOW WAS BLOCKED EMPLOYING 4"X 6" LUMBER. THERE REMAINED A VOID OF 24" ABAFT THE STOW. THE DRUMS, IN-WAY OF THE SECOND TIER, WERE FOUND DISPLACED OFF THEIR PALLET AND THE STEEL TENSION BANDS TO HAVE PARTED.  THE DRUMS WERE FOUND LYING ON THEIR SIDE IN-WAY OF THE FORWARD SECTION OF THE CONTAINER. THE ENTIRE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER WAS FOUND TO BE SOAKED IN VARNISH AND DRUMS STOWED IN THE FORWARD SECTION OF THE CONTAINER TO HAVE THEIR SIDE DELUGED IN VARNISH. A TOTAL OF TWO (2) DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING AND HENCE THEY WERE SET IN SALVAGE DRUMS. IT WAS COMMENTED Y OUR SURVEYOR THAT THE 3 DRUMS IN THE SECOND TIER WEE NOT ADEQUATELY SECURED FOR OCEAN SHIPMENT. ONE 3/4" TENSION BAND AND A 2" LUMBER BRACE IS NOT CONSIDERED ADEQUATE SECURING. FOSS PROVIDED THE NECESSARY PERSONNEL AND EQUIPMENT TO CLEAN THE INSIDE OF THE 20FT CONTAINER AT T-6 PORTLAND. THE OTHER 33 GOOD ORDER DRUMS WERE T/L INTO CONTAINER CAXU2054210 BY FOSS. THE COAST GUARD PLACED A HOLD ON THIS CONTAINER TO MAKE SURE THE DRUMS THAT HAD THEIR SIDES DELUGED IN THE VARNISH HAD ALL BEEN CLEANED BEFORE TAKING THE CONTAINER OFF HOLD. THE COAS
OVER FILL STORAGE TANK OF #2 HOME HEATING OIL.
